Now we can prove the norm version of the H√∂lder inequality:

```tactics
end Real

section Hoelder
variable {őĪ : Type*} {mőĪ : MeasurableSpace őĪ} [DiscreteMeasurableSpace őĪ] [Fintype őĪ] [RCLike ūĚēú]
  {p q r : ‚ĄĚ‚Č•0‚ąě} {f g : őĪ ‚Üí ūĚēú}
```

First, we prove that the norm of an inner product is less than or equal to the inner product of norms:

```tactics
lemma norm_wInner_cWeight_le (f g : őĪ ‚Üí ūĚēú) :
    ‚ÄĖ‚ü™f, g‚üę‚āô_[ūĚēú]‚ÄĖ‚āä ‚Č§ ‚ü™fun a ‚Ü¶ ‚ÄĖf a‚ÄĖ, fun a ‚Ü¶ ‚ÄĖg a‚ÄĖ‚üę‚āô_[‚ĄĚ] := by
  simpa [wInner_cWeight_eq_expect, norm_mul, mul_comm]
    using norm_expect_le (K := ‚ĄĚ) (f := fun i ‚Ü¶ conj (f i) * g i)
```

Next, we prove the H√∂lder inequality for norms:

```tactics
/-- **H√∂lder's inequality**, binary case. -/
lemma nnnorm_wInner_cWeight_le_dLpNorm_mul_dLpNorm (p q : ‚ĄĚ‚Č•0‚ąě) [p.HolderConjugate q] :
    ‚ÄĖ‚ü™f, g‚üę‚āô_[ūĚēú]‚ÄĖ‚āä ‚Č§ ‚ÄĖf‚ÄĖ‚āô_[p] * ‚ÄĖg‚ÄĖ‚āô_[q] :=
  calc
    _ ‚Č§ ‚ü™fun a ‚Ü¶ ‚ÄĖf a‚ÄĖ, fun a ‚Ü¶ ‚ÄĖg a‚ÄĖ‚üę‚āô_[‚ĄĚ] := norm_wInner_cWeight_le _ _
    _ ‚Č§ ‚ÄĖfun a ‚Ü¶ ‚ÄĖf a‚ÄĖ‚ÄĖ‚āô_[p] * ‚ÄĖfun a ‚Ü¶ ‚ÄĖg a‚ÄĖ‚ÄĖ‚āô_[q] := wInner_cWeight_le_cLpNorm_mul_cLpNorm _ _
    _ = ‚ÄĖf‚ÄĖ‚āô_[p] * ‚ÄĖg‚ÄĖ‚āô_[q] := by simp_rw [cLpNorm_norm]
```

Finally, we prove the main Holder's inequality for products of functions:

```tactics
/-- **H√∂lder's inequality**, binary case. -/
lemma cLpNorm_mul_le (p q : ‚ĄĚ‚Č•0‚ąě) (hr‚āÄ : r ‚Č† 0) [hpqr : ENNReal.HolderTriple p q r] :
    ‚ÄĖf * g‚ÄĖ‚āô_[r] ‚Č§ ‚ÄĖf‚ÄĖ‚āô_[p] * ‚ÄĖg‚ÄĖ‚āô_[q] := by
  obtain rfl | p := p
  ¬∑ sorry
  obtain rfl | q := q
  ¬∑ sorry
  obtain rfl | r := r
  ¬∑ sorry
```

The error occurs at the end of the `sorry` block. We need to replace the `sorry` with a valid proof. The goal at this point is `‚äĘ p ‚Č† 0`.

Looking at the context, we have `p : ‚ĄĚ‚Č•0‚ąě`. In Lean's `NNReal` (non-negative real numbers including infinity), a value `x` is not equal to `0` if `x` is positive or if `x` is infinity. Since `p` is an exponent in `‚ÄĖf‚ÄĖ‚āô_[p]`, it's conventional that `p > 0` (or `p = ‚ąě`). If `p = 0`, then `‚ÄĖf‚ÄĖ‚āô_[0] = 0` for any `f` when `0 < 0` is false. However, Holder's inequality typically requires positive exponents.

